then add that I've been sick for coming on 3-4 weeks now, with a variety of bugs. We wrote it off as daycare bugs, but I wake up being unable to breathe, my head pounds, I feel lightheaded and don't have much appetite. 

I am just a mess of worry. I know I'm not alone.

If there was good testing capacity, and lots of information/reports transparently sharing the situation, I'd be less worried without mandates. But right now, I have no way to know whats wrong with my son - and I worry so much it's long covid. Logically or not.

I am unsure about how to protect my family from an ongoing pandemic while living in a province that is pretending it isn't happening. Data from across the world is showing the results removing health restrictions, and its not good. 

I am so scared for my family.

My anxiety is on defcon 1. But not sure it's wrong to be worried...

Back to 'productivity' first, health last again. 

We learned absolutely NOTHING as a society about how to be empathetic and caring to the greater population, did we?

I have been really trying not to be 'that guy', but it feels like there is less and less space for concern around COVID effects and health. I know there is a war going on - but I still worry, as this pandemic is not over.

I know it's important for many to see and converse with colleagues in person, but in reality, I will be sitting at a desk in a mostly empty office, doing the meetings the same way I did at home. On Teams. 

Only thing that changes is the amount of risk I'm bringing into my home.

How many times have we heard of doctors/health professionals refusing to listen to parents because it wasn't 'proven' with a test? Will he get the help he needs? 

Add to that that I'm going back to the office for 2-3 days a week starting mid-month, and I'm a bit of a mess.

In a province where I can't get a PCR for my kid, rapid tests aren't recommended or accurate (as per MB Health for kids under 2), so we have no way to know. 

What if he did have COVID and has effects in the future, but I can't actually prove he had it due to NO testing?

I know it's not super common - but at the same time, we don't know enough about what COVID does long-term to the body, we have no idea. Add to the fact that my son isn't vaccinated, and there is NO vaccines available for him, and I just feel absolutely powerless to keep him safe.

I just can't stop worrying about my family's health, what long covid may mean and how I am increasingly surrounded by people who want to "just get covid" and get it over with. 

It really scares me, I don't know how to protect my family in this province.

I have been NAILING the work so far. It's going to get busier, more stress, more things happening, but I'm confident I can handle it. I'm confident I have more tools - more ability - and more mental clarity with the ADHD med regime. 

I am so thankful. That's all I keep thinking.

I'm awash with feelings of health, pride in the work I've been putting in for over 7 years now. Some left, some walked away - but I continued to work on myself, strived to be better for not only myself but for the people around me. 

I am practically gushing. It's so weird.

I had the incredible belief of others. People I worked with, who knew me at my best. Who understood the struggle of mental illness, anxiety, depression and ADHD. 

I have missed ONE day since being back, and it was daycare's fault. Not once did I miss work because of anxiety!!

I feel so good. Proud of myself, and it's such a refreshing feeling. 3 months ago I thought I could never work in any capacity, ever again. I was extremely low. 

Then, I had a chance to go back to a job I struggled in a year ago. I missed days due to anxiety. I wasn't happy.

I wonder when I won't feel that loss anymore. I hope it's sooner than later, even tho I'll always hope to see a text from a couple of those long-lost best friends.

Thanks for letting me vent, once again. I really should have a journal, but isn't that what Twitter is?

Just because I can't connect and apologize for my part in adding stress to their lives during a STRESSFUL time for EVERYONE, doesn't mean I'm not sorry, or that I can't move on. I am SO remorseful.

I have genuinely tried to reconnect. But the sadness, the loss, it lingers.

I mean, a global pandemic? While also having my first child? While dealing with generalized anxiety, depression and untreated ADHD?!

Yea, it's no wonder I was trauma dumping. And, I've said sorry, but I'm not going to carry this feeling of guilt forever.

This attitude became something these friends believed, never seeing the work I was putting in to get well, the struggle I was having during a pandemic and the birth of my first child. 

It's reasonable to think, looking back, that I was out of my mind, and really struggling.

It's been over a year. My former friends chose to side with someone they knew treated me unfairly, constantly - and would openly make fun of me, my family, etc, in the name of "jokes". 

Meanwhile, my mental health was seen as me "being the victim" and "always making an excuse".

While I'm stronger, healthier and more aware of how my mental health struggles can affect those around me, I'm not perfect. It was never intentional. 

But the hurt one of these former friends inflicted on me over a period of years is the heart of the issue.

I only reached out to those with who I still felt safe, still believed there was a genuine connection. One responded he wasn't ready to chat, maybe never will. That hurts, really still does.

Another has ignored me on every platform, in the two attempts I've made.

It's been over a year, and I still find myself missing/thinking about my old friends. A friendship breakup sucks. 

With a clearer mind, I understand my mistakes - I was trauma dumping EVERY single day. I've tried to reach out and apologize, taken accountability for my mistakes.

Until we see REAL funding, accessible & free mental health specialists/programs, I'll continue to say we need to do more. 

Thanks for reading.

#mentalhealth #stigma #anxiety #adhd #depression #mentalhealthday https://t.co/4oOdsevw6o

I was struggling, and was taken advantage of. I've even been bullied by those in positions of power, once they saw my struggle.

/8

I've lost several jobs due to being honest, taking a health leave and returning after getting on top of my health. I've been forced to sign a NDA to allow a health provider (for mental illness) to fire me without being at risk of human rights or labour law violations.

/7

Carey Price announced he was stepping away from hockey to get well, and his wife confirmed it was related to mental health. I'm thankful he is able to get help, without risking his employment, still getting paid. EVERY Canadian should have this option. Right now most don't.

/6

Sadly not every business is able to provide these benefits. 

I'm lucky because I was able to access a specialist through a referral, and I'm thankful every day for my doctors/therapists. Each of them have had a lasting effect on my well being and my ability to be self-aware.

/5

It should be as easy to get to a clinic or a family doctor when we are trying to access support from mental health specialists. Right now, we rely on businesses to provide additional benefits, Employee Assistance Programs and to treat mental health with dignity and respect.

/4

Right now, if I want to get support for my struggles without paying, I have to attend a large public meeting in a group, go through exercises and reading that only elevates my struggles and makes it HARDER to access help without paying per session.

/3

However, as someone who has struggled with depression, generalized anxiety, self esteem, self confidence and ADHD, we need MORE than awareness and conversations. We need further investment in mental health supports and programs to make getting help easy and affordable (free!).
/2

(Mental Health 🧵)

So yesterday was #worldmentalhealthday - an annual day where folks share their struggles and talk about how important mental health is. I'm thankful for these conversations.
